{"title_page": "Erling Jepsen", "text_new": "[[File:Erling Jepsen (Cropped, 2014).jpg|thumb|Erling Jepsen (2014)]]\n'''Erling Jepsen''' (born May 14, 1956 in [[Gram (Denmark)|Gram, Denmark]]) is a Danish author and playwright.<ref name=\"CodySprinchorn2007\">{{cite book|last1=Cody|first1=Gabrielle H.|last2=Sprinchorn|first2=Evert|title=The Columbia Encyclopedia of Modern Drama|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qYfH1tOwsHcC&pg=PA733|accessdate=30 November 2014|year=2007|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=9780231144223|pages=733\u2013}}</ref> His novel ''Frygtelig lykkelig'' (''Terribly Happy'') was adapted into the 2008 neo-noir thriller ''[[Terribly Happy]]'',<ref>{{cite book|title=Historical Dictionary of Scandinavian Cinema|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ae4QqlUDt9wC&pg=PA176|date=2012-08-31|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=9780810855243|pages=176\u2013}}</ref> and his [[autobiographical novel]] ''Kunsten at Gr\u00e6de i Kor ''(''The Art of Crying'')'' ''was adapted into the 2006 film ''[[The Art of Crying]]''.<ref name=\"Smith2008\">{{cite book|last=Smith|first=Ian Haydn|title=TCM International Film Guide 2008: The Definitive Annual Review of World Cinema|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qUMNAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=30 November 2014|year=2008|publisher=Wallflower Press|isbn=9781905674619}}</ref>\n\nJepsen won the 2004 [[Holberg Medal]] for his contributions to Danish drama.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.b.dk/kultur/det-regner-med-holberg-priser|title=Det regner med Holberg-priser|last=Myhre|first=Dorte|date=December 2, 2004|language=Danish|accessdate=30 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jepsen, Erling}}\n[[Category:20th-century Danish dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Danish male novelists]]\n[[Category:Danish male dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century Danish novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Danish novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Danish male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Danish male writers]]\n\n\n{{Denmark-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Erling Jepsen (Cropped, 2014).jpg|thumb|Erling Jepsen (2014)]]\n'''Erling Jepsen''' (born May 14, 1956 in [[Gram (Denmark)|Gram, Denmark]]) is a Danish author and playwright.<ref name=\"CodySprinchorn2007\">{{cite book|last1=Cody|first1=Gabrielle H.|last2=Sprinchorn|first2=Evert|title=The Columbia Encyclopedia of Modern Drama|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qYfH1tOwsHcC&pg=PA733|accessdate=30 November 2014|year=2007|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=9780231144223|pages=733\u2013}}</ref> His novel ''Frygtelig lykkelig'' (''Terribly Happy'') was adapted into the 2008 neo-noir thriller ''[[Terribly Happy]]'',<ref>{{cite book|title=Historical Dictionary of Scandinavian Cinema|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ae4QqlUDt9wC&pg=PA176|date=2012-08-31|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=9780810855243|pages=176\u2013}}</ref> and his [[autobiographical novel]] ''Kunsten at Gr\u00e6de i Kor ''(''The Art of Crying'')'' ''was adapted into the 2006 film ''[[The Art of Crying]]''.<ref name=\"Smith2008\">{{cite book|last=Smith|first=Ian Haydn|title=TCM International Film Guide 2008: The Definitive Annual Review of World Cinema|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qUMNAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=30 November 2014|year=2008|publisher=Wallflower Press|isbn=9781905674619}}</ref>\n\nJepsen won the 2004 [[Holberg Medal]] for his contributions to Danish drama.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.b.dk/kultur/det-regner-med-holberg-priser|title=Det regner med Holberg-priser|last=Myhre|first=Dorte|date=December 2, 2004|language=Danish|accessdate=30 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jepsen, Erling}}\n[[Category:20th-century Danish dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Danish male novelists]]\n[[Category:Danish male dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century Danish novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Danish novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Danish male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n\n\n{{Denmark-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Erling_Jepsen"}
{"title_page": "Peter H\u00f8eg", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| image       = Peter H\u00f8eg.jpg\n| name        = Peter H\u00f8eg\n| pseudonym   =\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1957|5|17|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Copenhagen]]\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| occupation  = Author\n| nationality = Danish\n| period      = 1988\u2013present\n| genre       = fiction, recent history\n| subject     =\n| movement    =\n| signature   =\n| website     =\n}}\n'''Peter H\u00f8eg''' (born 17 May 1957)<ref name=\"Britannica\">{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/biography/Peter-Hoeg|title=Peter H\u00f8eg|last=Blumberg|first=Naomi|publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|accessdate=9 November 2015}}</ref> is a Danish writer of fiction. He is best known for his novel,  ''[[Miss Smilla's Feeling for Snow]]'' (1992).\n\n==Early life==\nH\u00f8eg was born in [[Copenhagen]], Denmark. Before becoming a writer, he worked variously as a sailor, ballet dancer and actor (in addition to fencing and [[mountaineering]])\u2014experiences that he uses in his novels. He received a [[Master of Arts]] in Literature from the [[University of Copenhagen]] in 1984.\n\n==Career==\nPeter H\u00f8eg published his first novel, ''A History of Danish Dreams'', in 1988 to very positive reviews. He decided at that stage to protect his personal life.{{r|phtele}} Over the next five years he wrote and published the short story collection ''[[Tales of the Night (H\u00f8eg book)|Tales of Night]]'', and the novels: ''Miss Smilla's Feeling for Snow'' (1992), ''[[Borderliners]]'' (1993). It was ''Miss Smilla's Feeling for Snow'' that earned H\u00f8eg immediate and international literary celebrity.{{Citation needed|date=June 2015}} In 1993 he won the Danish booksellers award [[De Gyldne Laurb\u00e6r]] (The Golden Laurel) and the [[Danish Critics Prize for Literature]]<ref>[http://www.litteraturpriser.dk/kritiker.htm Litteraturpriser.dk] Kritikerprisen</ref> for his book ''De m\u00e5ske egnede'' (English title: ''Borderliners'').<ref>[http://www.boghandlerklubben.dk/side1.html Boghandlerklubben.dk] De Gyldne Laurb\u00e6r</ref>\n\nH\u00f8eg virtually disappeared in 1996 after the lukewarm reception of ''[[The Woman and the Ape]]''.<ref>[http://www.forfatterweb.dk/oversigt/hoeeg-peter/hele-portraettet-om-peter-hoeeg Forfatterweb.dk] written by Pia Andersen H\u00f8g in Dagbladet Information, 2011 (''in Danish'')</ref>\n\n===Return and ''The Quiet Girl'' controversy===\nH\u00f8eg resurfaced in 2006 with ''[[The Quiet Girl]]'', his first novel in 10 years. At the time of its publication, reception in Denmark was mixed at best, and the novel was generally disregarded as being either too complex or too postmodern.<ref>Juul, Marianne, (Translated by John Mason). [http://www.danishliterarymagazine.info/f4e0029 \"Peter H\u00f8eg: Breaks the Silence\"]. Danish Literary Magazine. Fall 2006.  {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20070705101829/http://www.danishliterarymagazine.info/f4e0029 |date=5 July 2007 }}</ref>\n\nH\u00f8eg was surprised by response and has since said the complexity of the book was nowhere near that of films like ''Inception'' or ''Memento''.{{r|phtele}} Norwegian author [[Jan Kj\u00e6rstad]] defended the book, saying: \"it surprises me that a novel written by someone of Peter H\u00f8eg\u2019s calibre, with such great intelligence, so much thought and originality, should be treated to such outpourings of pettiness and virulence.  How could such a rollicking, generous, open book be greeted with so much gravity and severity, such closed minds and again: in my broad-minded old Denmark?\"<ref>Kj\u00e6rstad, Jan. ''Politiken''. 3 June 2006.</ref>\n\nIn October 2007, the Danish literary critic Poul Behrendt published a book entitled ''Den Hemmelige Note: Ti kapitler om sm\u00e5 ting der forandrer alt'', in which he explains that the cold reception of ''The Quiet Girl'' was due to its complexity and scope which the critics, according to Behrendt, didn't understand.<ref>Skriver, Svend. Ekstra Bladet.  [http://ekstrabladet.dk/flash/anmeldelser/diverse/article350144.ece \"Oprejsning til Peter H\u00f8eg\"]. 21 October 2007.  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071023183004/http://ekstrabladet.dk/flash/anmeldelser/diverse/article350144.ece |date=23 October 2007 }}</ref>{{Citation needed|date=October 2007}}\n\nIn 2014, his latest book, ''The Susan Effect'' (''Effekten af Susan'') was published in Denmark. The book is described by ''[[The Economist]]'' as a \"high-concept thriller\" featuring [[Social disintegration|social breakdown]], [[environmental disaster]], and [[Nuclear weapon|atomic weapons]] in rogue hands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.economist.com/books-and-arts/2017/08/24/peter-hoegs-new-novel-is-a-high-concept-thriller|title=Peter Hoeg\u2019s new novel is a high-concept thriller|accessdate=25 March 2020|via=The Economist}}</ref>\n\n==Style==\n[[File:Peter H\u00f8eg 2012.jpg|thumbnail|Peter H\u00f8eg (2012)]]\nH\u00f8eg has a reputation for being hard to place in terms of literary style. All his works are stylistically very different from one another, and have been labelled postmodern, gothic, magical-realist, to mention a few. While ''Miss Smilla'', for instance, was classified as [[Nordic noir]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/19/books/review/robert-karjel-after-the-monsoon.html|title=Nordic Noir, in the Horn of Africa|last=Pavone|first=Chris|date=2018-07-19|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-02-15|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> ''The Susan Effect'' featured magical elements such as in the case of the Svendsen family, which possessed one superpower or another in the narrative.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theartsdesk.com/books/peter-h%C3%B8eg-susan-effect-review-nordic-noir-turns-surreal|title=Peter H\u00f8eg: The Susan Effect review - Nordic noir turns surreal|website=theartsdesk.com|access-date=2019-02-15}}</ref> There is a thread to be found, however, in terms of theme; H\u00f8eg's work often seems to deal with the consequences of the progress of civilisation.<ref>Egesholm, Christian. [http://www.danishliterature.info/fa20029/Action/002/fid/39/lang/eng \"Peter H\u00f8eg\"]. Danish Literary Magazine. Fall 2007. {{dead link|date=December 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview, H\u00f8eg said that he follows a contemplative approach to his writing practices and this involved a pattern \"of meditating, then writing, then meditating and then writing again.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/bookreviews/9587052/A-Page-in-the-Life-Peter-Hoeg.html|title=A Page in the Life: Peter Hoeg|last=House|first=Christian|date=2012-10-10|work=Telegraph|access-date=2019-02-15|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nH\u00f8eg grew up in Copenhagen and lives now in N\u00f8rre Snede in [[Jutland]].<ref name=\"N\u00f8rre Snede\">{{cite web|url=http://www.information.dk/111090|title=Fanden l\u00f8s i N\u00f8rre Snede|last=Bj\u00f8rnkj\u00e6r|first=Kirsten|date=25 August 2005|publisher=Information|language=Danish|accessdate=9 November 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"School teacher\">{{cite web|url=http://aoh.dk/artikel/peter-heg-skal-vre-skolelrer-i-nrre-snede|title=Peter H\u00f8eg skal v\u00e6re skolel\u00e6rer i N\u00f8rre Snede|last=Kristensen|first=Kim|date=23 January 2015|publisher=Mediehuset Herning Folkeblad|language=Danish|accessdate=9 November 2015}}</ref> He has four children.<ref name=\"Berlingske 2014\">{{cite web|url=http://www.b.dk/kultur/jeg-fortryder-intet|title=\u00bbJeg fortryder intet\u00ab|last=Bangsgaard|first=Jeppe|date=16 May 2014|publisher=Berlingske|language=Danish|accessdate=9 November 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Rosinante\">{{cite web|url=http://rosinante-co.dk/forfattere/peter-hoeeg|title=Forfatter Peter H\u00f8eg|publisher=Rosinante & Co|language=Danish|accessdate=9 November 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Ekstra Bladet 2010\">{{cite web|url=http://ekstrabladet.dk/flash/dkkendte/article4146332.ece|title=Peter H\u00f8eg: Mit liv matcher ikke myten|last=Hansen|first=Frank Sebastian|date=3 September 2010|publisher=Ekstra Bladet|language=Danish|accessdate=9 November 2015}}</ref> In 1996 he established the Lolwe foundation which provides financial assistance to women and children in the third world, especially in Africa and Tibetan exile areas.<ref name=\"Dr.dk Tema\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dr.dk/skole/Dansk/Danske_forfattere/Peter_hoeg/peter-hoeg.htm|title=Tema Danske forfattere - Peter H\u00f8eg|publisher=Dr.dk|language=Danish|accessdate=9 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\nH\u00f8eg's books are published in Denmark by Munksgaard/Rosinante, now a part of [[Blackwell Publishing]], and have also been published in more than 30 other countries.\n\n*''[[The History of Danish Dreams]]'' (Forestilling om det Tyvende \u00e5rhundrede), 1988\n*''[[Tales of the Night (H\u00f8eg book)|Tales of the Night]]'' (Fort\u00e6llinger om natten), 1990\n*''[[Miss Smilla's Feeling for Snow]]'' (US: ''Smilla's Sense of Snow'') (Frk. Smillas fornemmelse for sne), 1992, later filmed by [[Bille August]]\n*''[[Borderliners]]'' (De m\u00e5ske egnede), 1993\n*''[[The Woman and The Ape]]'' (Kvinden og aben), 1996\n*''[[The Quiet Girl]]'' (Den stille pige), 2006\n* ''[[The Elephant Keepers' Children]]'' (Elefantpassernes b\u00f8rn), 2010\n* ''The Susan Effect'' (Effekten af Susan), Rosinante, 2014<ref name=\"Effekten af Susan\">{{cite web|url=http://www.litteratursiden.dk/anmeldelser/effekten-af-susan-af-peter-hoeeg|title=Effekten af Susan af Peter H\u00f8eg|date=27 May 2014|publisher=Litteratursiden.dk|language=Danish|accessdate=9 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151123032843/http://www.litteratursiden.dk/anmeldelser/effekten-af-susan-af-peter-hoeeg|archive-date=23 November 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=phtele>{{cite web|last1=House|first1=Christian|title=A Page in the Life: Peter Hoeg|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/bookreviews/9587052/A-Page-in-the-Life-Peter-Hoeg.html|publisher=TelegraphChristian House|accessdate=3 June 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070704181904/http://www.ambwashington.um.dk/en/menu/InformationaboutDenmark/Culture/Literature/PeterH%C3%B8eg.htm Peter H\u00f8eg's biography] published by the Royal Danish Embassy in Washington DC\n<!-- * [http://www.boheme-magazine.net/php/modules.php?name=News&file=article&sid=387 Boh\u00e8me Magazine] Article about ''Smilla's Sense of Snow'' LINK BROKEN, link hidden on 17 January 2010 -->\n*{{in lang|ru}} [http://eldb.net/name/nm005510/ The Electronic Literary Database]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091205210109/http://www.podst.ru/?area=posts&id=361 Silence. Peter H\u00f8eg's Interview for Russia, 2007] Radio feature, in Russian, English transcript available. Podstantsiya.ru\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hoeg, Peter}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Copenhagen alumni]]\n[[Category:Dilys Award winners]]\n[[Category:Danish male novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Danish novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Danish novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Danish male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Danish male writers]]\n[[Category:Denmark Noir writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| image       = Peter H\u00f8eg.jpg\n| name        = Peter H\u00f8eg\n| pseudonym   =\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1957|5|17|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Copenhagen]]\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| occupation  = Author\n| nationality = Danish\n| period      = 1988\u2013present\n| genre       = fiction, recent history\n| subject     =\n| movement    =\n| signature   =\n| website     =\n}}\n'''Peter H\u00f8eg''' (born 17 May 1957)<ref name=\"Britannica\">{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/biography/Peter-Hoeg|title=Peter H\u00f8eg|last=Blumberg|first=Naomi|publisher=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|accessdate=9 November 2015}}</ref> is a Danish writer of fiction. He is best known for his novel,  ''[[Miss Smilla's Feeling for Snow]]'' (1992). \n\n==Early life==\nH\u00f8eg was born in [[Copenhagen]], Denmark. Before becoming a writer, he worked variously as a sailor, ballet dancer and actor (in addition to fencing and [[mountaineering]])\u2014experiences that he uses in his novels. He received a [[Master of Arts]] in Literature from the [[University of Copenhagen]] in 1984.\n\n==Career==\nPeter H\u00f8eg published his first novel, ''A History of Danish Dreams'', in 1988 to very positive reviews. He decided at that stage to protect his personal life.{{r|phtele}} Over the next five years he wrote and published the short story collection ''[[Tales of the Night (H\u00f8eg book)|Tales of Night]]'', and the novels: ''Miss Smilla's Feeling for Snow'' (1992), ''[[Borderliners]]'' (1993). It was ''Miss Smilla's Feeling for Snow'' that earned H\u00f8eg immediate and international literary celebrity.{{Citation needed|date=June 2015}} In 1993 he won the Danish booksellers award [[De Gyldne Laurb\u00e6r]] (The Golden Laurel) and the [[Danish Critics Prize for Literature]]<ref>[http://www.litteraturpriser.dk/kritiker.htm Litteraturpriser.dk] Kritikerprisen</ref> for his book ''De m\u00e5ske egnede'' (English title: ''Borderliners'').<ref>[http://www.boghandlerklubben.dk/side1.html Boghandlerklubben.dk] De Gyldne Laurb\u00e6r</ref>\n\nH\u00f8eg virtually disappeared in 1996 after the lukewarm reception of ''[[The Woman and the Ape]]''.<ref>[http://www.forfatterweb.dk/oversigt/hoeeg-peter/hele-portraettet-om-peter-hoeeg Forfatterweb.dk] written by Pia Andersen H\u00f8g in Dagbladet Information, 2011 (''in Danish'')</ref>\n\n===Return and ''The Quiet Girl'' controversy===\nH\u00f8eg resurfaced in 2006 with ''[[The Quiet Girl]]'', his first novel in 10 years. At the time of its publication, reception in Denmark was mixed at best, and the novel was generally disregarded as being either too complex or too postmodern.<ref>Juul, Marianne, (Translated by John Mason). [http://www.danishliterarymagazine.info/f4e0029 \"Peter H\u00f8eg: Breaks the Silence\"]. Danish Literary Magazine. Fall 2006.  {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20070705101829/http://www.danishliterarymagazine.info/f4e0029 |date=5 July 2007 }}</ref>\n\nH\u00f8eg was surprised by response and has since said the complexity of the book was nowhere near that of films like ''Inception'' or ''Memento''.{{r|phtele}} Norwegian author [[Jan Kj\u00e6rstad]] defended the book, saying: \"it surprises me that a novel written by someone of Peter H\u00f8eg\u2019s calibre, with such great intelligence, so much thought and originality, should be treated to such outpourings of pettiness and virulence.  How could such a rollicking, generous, open book be greeted with so much gravity and severity, such closed minds and again: in my broad-minded old Denmark?\"<ref>Kj\u00e6rstad, Jan. ''Politiken''. 3 June 2006.</ref>\n\nIn October 2007, the Danish literary critic Poul Behrendt published a book entitled ''Den Hemmelige Note: Ti kapitler om sm\u00e5 ting der forandrer alt'', in which he explains that the cold reception of ''The Quiet Girl'' was due to its complexity and scope which the critics, according to Behrendt, didn't understand.<ref>Skriver, Svend. Ekstra Bladet.  [http://ekstrabladet.dk/flash/anmeldelser/diverse/article350144.ece \"Oprejsning til Peter H\u00f8eg\"]. 21 October 2007.  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071023183004/http://ekstrabladet.dk/flash/anmeldelser/diverse/article350144.ece |date=23 October 2007 }}</ref>{{Citation needed|date=October 2007}}\n\nIn 2014, his latest book, ''The Susan Effect'' (''Effekten af Susan'') was published in Denmark. The book is described by ''[[The Economist]]'' as a \"high-concept thriller\" featuring [[Social disintegration|social breakdown]], [[Environmental disaster|environmental disaster]], and [[Nuclear weapon|atomic weapons]] in rogue hands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.economist.com/books-and-arts/2017/08/24/peter-hoegs-new-novel-is-a-high-concept-thriller|title=Peter Hoeg\u2019s new novel is a high-concept thriller|accessdate=25 March 2020|via=The Economist}}</ref>\n\n==Style==\n[[File:Peter H\u00f8eg 2012.jpg|thumbnail|Peter H\u00f8eg (2012)]]\nH\u00f8eg has a reputation for being hard to place in terms of literary style. All his works are stylistically very different from one another, and have been labelled postmodern, gothic, magical-realist, to mention a few. While ''Miss Smilla'', for instance, was classified as [[Nordic noir]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/19/books/review/robert-karjel-after-the-monsoon.html|title=Nordic Noir, in the Horn of Africa|last=Pavone|first=Chris|date=2018-07-19|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-02-15|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> ''The Susan Effect'' featured magical elements such as in the case of the Svendsen family, which possessed one superpower or another in the narrative.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theartsdesk.com/books/peter-h%C3%B8eg-susan-effect-review-nordic-noir-turns-surreal|title=Peter H\u00f8eg: The Susan Effect review - Nordic noir turns surreal|website=theartsdesk.com|access-date=2019-02-15}}</ref> There is a thread to be found, however, in terms of theme; H\u00f8eg's work often seems to deal with the consequences of the progress of civilisation.<ref>Egesholm, Christian. [http://www.danishliterature.info/fa20029/Action/002/fid/39/lang/eng \"Peter H\u00f8eg\"]. Danish Literary Magazine. Fall 2007. {{dead link|date=December 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview, H\u00f8eg said that he follows a contemplative approach to his writing practices and this involved a pattern \"of meditating, then writing, then meditating and then writing again.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/bookreviews/9587052/A-Page-in-the-Life-Peter-Hoeg.html|title=A Page in the Life: Peter Hoeg|last=House|first=Christian|date=2012-10-10|work=Telegraph|access-date=2019-02-15|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> \n\n==Personal life==\nH\u00f8eg grew up in Copenhagen and lives now in N\u00f8rre Snede in [[Jutland]].<ref name=\"N\u00f8rre Snede\">{{cite web|url=http://www.information.dk/111090|title=Fanden l\u00f8s i N\u00f8rre Snede|last=Bj\u00f8rnkj\u00e6r|first=Kirsten|date=25 August 2005|publisher=Information|language=Danish|accessdate=9 November 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"School teacher\">{{cite web|url=http://aoh.dk/artikel/peter-heg-skal-vre-skolelrer-i-nrre-snede|title=Peter H\u00f8eg skal v\u00e6re skolel\u00e6rer i N\u00f8rre Snede|last=Kristensen|first=Kim|date=23 January 2015|publisher=Mediehuset Herning Folkeblad|language=Danish|accessdate=9 November 2015}}</ref> He has four children.<ref name=\"Berlingske 2014\">{{cite web|url=http://www.b.dk/kultur/jeg-fortryder-intet|title=\u00bbJeg fortryder intet\u00ab|last=Bangsgaard|first=Jeppe|date=16 May 2014|publisher=Berlingske|language=Danish|accessdate=9 November 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Rosinante\">{{cite web|url=http://rosinante-co.dk/forfattere/peter-hoeeg|title=Forfatter Peter H\u00f8eg|publisher=Rosinante & Co|language=Danish|accessdate=9 November 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Ekstra Bladet 2010\">{{cite web|url=http://ekstrabladet.dk/flash/dkkendte/article4146332.ece|title=Peter H\u00f8eg: Mit liv matcher ikke myten|last=Hansen|first=Frank Sebastian|date=3 September 2010|publisher=Ekstra Bladet|language=Danish|accessdate=9 November 2015}}</ref> In 1996 he established the Lolwe foundation which provides financial assistance to women and children in the third world, especially in Africa and Tibetan exile areas.<ref name=\"Dr.dk Tema\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dr.dk/skole/Dansk/Danske_forfattere/Peter_hoeg/peter-hoeg.htm|title=Tema Danske forfattere - Peter H\u00f8eg|publisher=Dr.dk|language=Danish|accessdate=9 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\nH\u00f8eg's books are published in Denmark by Munksgaard/Rosinante, now a part of [[Blackwell Publishing]], and have also been published in more than 30 other countries.\n\n*''[[The History of Danish Dreams]]'' (Forestilling om det Tyvende \u00e5rhundrede), 1988\n*''[[Tales of the Night (H\u00f8eg book)|Tales of the Night]]'' (Fort\u00e6llinger om natten), 1990\n*''[[Miss Smilla's Feeling for Snow]]'' (US: ''Smilla's Sense of Snow'') (Frk. Smillas fornemmelse for sne), 1992, later filmed by [[Bille August]]\n*''[[Borderliners]]'' (De m\u00e5ske egnede), 1993\n*''[[The Woman and The Ape]]'' (Kvinden og aben), 1996\n*''[[The Quiet Girl]]'' (Den stille pige), 2006\n* ''[[The Elephant Keepers' Children]]'' (Elefantpassernes b\u00f8rn), 2010\n* ''The Susan Effect'' (Effekten af Susan), Rosinante, 2014<ref name=\"Effekten af Susan\">{{cite web|url=http://www.litteratursiden.dk/anmeldelser/effekten-af-susan-af-peter-hoeeg|title=Effekten af Susan af Peter H\u00f8eg|date=27 May 2014|publisher=Litteratursiden.dk|language=Danish|accessdate=9 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151123032843/http://www.litteratursiden.dk/anmeldelser/effekten-af-susan-af-peter-hoeeg|archive-date=23 November 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=phtele>{{cite web|last1=House|first1=Christian|title=A Page in the Life: Peter Hoeg|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/bookreviews/9587052/A-Page-in-the-Life-Peter-Hoeg.html|publisher=TelegraphChristian House|accessdate=3 June 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070704181904/http://www.ambwashington.um.dk/en/menu/InformationaboutDenmark/Culture/Literature/PeterH%C3%B8eg.htm Peter H\u00f8eg's biography] published by the Royal Danish Embassy in Washington DC\n<!-- * [http://www.boheme-magazine.net/php/modules.php