cius''. Etymologically, the name means 'property owned by Patricius'.<ref name=\"Snoj\">{{cite book |last1=Snoj |first1=Marko |title=Etimolo\u0161ki slovar slovenskih zemljepisnih imen |date=2009 |publisher=Modrijan |location=Ljubljana |page=301}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.geopedia.si/Geopedia_en.html#L410_F10122996_T13_b4_x392318.8425_y38429.519_s14 Parecag on Geopedia]\n\n\n{{commons}}\n{{Piran}}\n{{Slovenian Riviera}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in the Municipality of Piran]]\n[[Category:Slovenian Riviera]]\n\n\n{{Piran-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Davemck", "label": "safe", "comment": "rmv duplicate parm", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parecag"}
{"title_page": "1971 Women's World Cup", "text_new": "{{Infobox tournament\n| name = Campeonato de F\u00fatbol Femenil\n| sport = [[Association football]]\n| year = 1971\n| image =\n| caption = \n| location =\n| start_date = <!-- or | date = -->\n| end_date =\n| established = \n| administrator =\n| tournament_format = \n| host = {{Flags|Mexico|text=}}\n| venues =\n| teams = 6\n| purse =\n| champions = {{Flags|Denmark|text=}} <!-- or | champion = -->\n| runners-up1 = {{Flags|Mexico|text=}} <!-- or | runner-up1 = -->\n| runners-up2 = <!-- or | runner-up2 = -->\n| matches = 11\n| points =\n| tries = \n| goals = 39\n| attendance = \n| noaverage = <!-- Set to 1 to exclude average attendance per match -->\n| mvp = \n| top_scorer = {{flagicon|DEN}} [[Susanne Augustesen]]<br>{{flagicon|DEN}} [[Lis Lene Nielsen]] (4 goals)\n| top_try_scorer = \n| stat1_label =\n| stat1 =\n| stat2_label =\n| stat2 =\n| stat3_label =\n| stat3 =\n| previous = \n| next = \n}}\n\nThe '''1971 Women's World Cup''' (Spanish: '''1971 Campeonato de F\u00fatbol Femenil''') was a non-[[FIFA]]-sanctioned [[association football]] tournament for women which took place in Mexico in August and September 1971. [[Denmark women's national football team|Denmark]] won the tournament.\n\n==Background==\nThe first unofficial Women's World Cup took place in [[1970 Women's World Cup|Italy in 1970]], also won by [[Denmark women's national football team|Denmark]].<ref name = \"Guardian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2015/jun/04/womens-world-cup-unofficial-record-breaking|title=Women\u2019s World Cup: from unofficial tournaments to record-breaking event|date=4 June 2015|accessdate=10 December 2018|author=Anna Kessel|publisher=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n==Qualifying==\nThe six-team tournament featured three different qualifying groups, two in Europe played in April and June 1971, and one in the Americas.<ref name = \"RSSSF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesm/mundo-women71.html|title=Mundial (Women) 1971|accessdate=10 December 2018|publisher=RSSSF}}</ref> Six teams made the final tournament \u2013 Mexico, Argentina, England, Denmark, France, and Italy.<ref name = \"RSSSF\"/> Four teams were knocked out in qualifying \u2013 Austria, the Netherlands, Sweden and Costa Rica.\n\nOne of the qualifiers was the first officially recognised women's international match. France beat the Netherlands 4-0 in Hazebrouck to qualify for the tournament in front of 1,500 spectators. However, the match was only recognised after it was completed, and the French players did not know they had qualified for the tournament until their coach told them after the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/womens-football/news/first-ladies-pave-the-way-1414187|title=First ladies pave the way|date=8 April 2011|publisher=FIFA.com}}</ref>\n\n==Tournament==\nTournament sponsors [[Martini & Rossi]] paid for each team's travel, accommodation, and kits.<ref name = \"BBC\"/> Goalposts were painted in pink hoops and stadium staff wore pink clothes, in order to try to appeal to women and families.<ref name = \"BBC\"/> Ticket prices ranged from 30 pesos (\u00a31.15) to 80 pesos (\u00a33).<ref name = \"BBC\"/> The tournament mascot was Xochitl, \"a young girl in [a] football kit\".<ref name = \"BBC\"/>\n\nAn estimated 80,000 people attended the Mexico group games against England and Argentina, and an estimated 110,000 attended the final, between Mexico and Denmark.<ref name = \"BBC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-46149887|title=Mexico 1971: When women's football hit the big time|date=7 December 2018|accessdate=10 December 2018|author=Bill Wilson|publisher=BBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"eluniversal\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/entrada-de-opinion/colaboracion/mochilazo-en-el-tiempo/nacion/sociedad/2017/03/8/el-mundial-femenil|title=El mundial femenil que M\u00e9xico olvid\u00f3|publisher=El Universal|date=8 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe hosts Mexico qualified for the final after defeating Italy in the semifinals. Two days before the final, the Mexican press noted the players for Mexico were unhappy they had not been receiving economic support for participating in the tournament. The Mexican team threatened to skip the final but gave up their two million peso demand and the game went forward as scheduled.<ref name=\"eluniversal\"/>\n\nDenmark won the tournament after beating Mexico 3\u20130 in the final, featuring a hat trick by 15-year-old [[Susanne Augustesen]].<ref name = \"RSSSF\"/> The victorious Danish team were treated to a celebratory reception at [[Copenhagen Town Hall]] upon their return from the tournament.<ref name = \"BT\"/> However, due to the unofficial nature of the tournament, it is not recognised by the [[Danish Football Association]].<ref name = \"BT\"/>\n\n==Squads==\nEngland's team included 13-year-old [[Leah Caleb]], 14-year-old [[Gill Sayell]], and 15-year-old [[Chris Lockwood (footballer)|Chris Lockwood]],<ref name = \"BBC\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://bbc.com/sport/extra/LNoYd7se8m/the-lost-lionesses|title=The lost lionesses|website=BBC Sport}}</ref> while 15-year-old Susanne Augustesen scored a hat-trick for Denmark as they beat Mexico 3\u20130 in the final.<ref name = \"RSSSF\"/> Augustesen was honoured by the mayor of her hometown, [[Holb\u00e6k]].<ref name = \"BT\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bt.dk/sport/verdensmester-som-15-aarig|title=Verdensmester som 15-\u00e5rig|date=10 September 2007|accessdate=10 December 2018|language=Danish|author=Nikoline Vestergaard|publisher=BT}}</ref>\n\n12 member of England's 14-woman squad reunited in June 2019 for the first time since the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48771268|title=Women's World Cup: 1971 'lost lionesses' squad tracked down after 48 years|date=26 June 2019|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==Group stage==\n===Group 1===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! width=20 | {{Toolti